{"id": "EUVD-2023-60409", "enisaUuid": "446f392d-67d7-3325-9653-434abf8a3a8b", "description": "In the Linux kernel, the following vulnerability has been resolved:\n\nm68k: Only force 030 bus error if PC not in exception table\n\n__get_kernel_nofault() does copy data in supervisor mode when\nforcing a task backtrace log through /proc/sysrq_trigger.\nThis is expected cause a bus error exception on e.g. NULL\npointer dereferencing when logging a kernel task has no\nworkqueue associated. This bus error ought to be ignored.\n\nOur 030 bus error handler is ill equipped to deal with this:\n\nWhenever ssw indicates a kernel mode access on a data fault,\nwe don't even attempt to handle the fault and instead always\nsend a SEGV signal (or panic). As a result, the check\nfor exception handling at the fault PC (buried in\nsend_sig_fault() which gets called from do_page_fault()\neventually) is never used.\n\nIn contrast, both 040 and 060 access error handlers do not\ncare whether a fault happened on supervisor mode access,\nand will call do_page_fault() on those, ultimately honoring\nthe exception table.\n\nAdd a check in bus_error030 to call do_page_fault() in case\nwe do have an entry for the fault PC in our exception table.\n\nI had attempted a fix for this earlier in 2019 that did rely\non testing pagefault_disabled() (see link below) to achieve\nthe same thing, but this patch should be more generic.\n\nTested on 030 Atari Falcon.", "datePublished": "2025-12-30T15:30:32", "dateUpdated": "2025-12-30T15:30:32", "baseScore": 0.0, "references": ["https://git.kernel.org/stable/c/1a6059f5ed57f48edfe7159404ff7d538d9d405b", "https://git.kernel.org/stable/c/f55cb52ec98b22125f5bda36391edb8894f7e8cf", "https://git.kernel.org/stable/c/2100e374251a8fc00cce1916cfc50f3cb652cbe3", "https://git.kernel.org/stable/c/df1da53a7e98f0b2a0eb2241c154f148f2f2c1d8", "https://git.kernel.org/stable/c/8bf8d5dade4c5e1d8a2386f29253ed28b5d87735", "https://git.kernel.org/stable/c/54fa25ffab2b700df5abd58c136d64a912c53953", "https://git.kernel.org/stable/c/ec15405b80fc15ffc87a23d01378ae061c1aba07", "https://git.kernel.org/stable/c/e36a82bebbf7da814530d5a179bef9df5934b717", "https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2023-54232"], "aliases": ["CVE-2023-54232"], "assigner": "Linux", "epss": 0.03, "enisaIdProduct": [{"id": "0785eb43-df00-3569-9726-8dd7ab2415fc", "product": {"name": "Linux"}, "product_version": "1da177e4c3f41524e886b7f1b8a0c1fc7321cac2 <f55cb52ec98b22125f5bda36391edb8894f7e8cf"}, {"id": "1cac64b8-2c5f-347c-b353-b709787e9f61", "product": {"name": "Linux"}, "product_version": "1da177e4c3f41524e886b7f1b8a0c1fc7321cac2 <e36a82bebbf7da814530d5a179bef9df5934b717"}, {"id": "3f93fe92-347f-36f6-8e49-5e340e014726", "product": {"name": "Linux"}, "product_version": "patch: 6.2.9"}, {"id": "4aef06f1-cb82-3a18-b069-154f49288529", "product": {"name": "Linux"}, "product_version": "patch: 6.3"}, {"id": "67c1fdea-ad8a-35ba-8edb-c1e47352d2a3", "product": {"name": "Linux"}, "product_version": "1da177e4c3f41524e886b7f1b8a0c1fc7321cac2 <1a6059f5ed57f48edfe7159404ff7d538d9d405b"}, {"id": "825c3fc2-e33c-31ad-ab62-ee6edf35e376", "product": {"name": "Linux"}, "product_version": "1da177e4c3f41524e886b7f1b8a0c1fc7321cac2 <8bf8d5dade4c5e1d8a2386f29253ed28b5d87735"}, {"id": "a5fef3a6-35d2-3dcb-8d10-f8d2a3f8bb56", "product": {"name": "Linux"}, "product_version": "patch: 5.15.105"}, {"id": "ba830e60-0cbf-34fa-8eb4-801ba76c57d3", "product": {"name": "Linux"}, "product_version": "patch: 6.1.22"}, {"id": "c964163f-dd2a-3f12-b1c2-982c71c3047b", "product": {"name": "Linux"}, "product_version": "patch: 4.19.280"}, {"id": "cb7b2eff-fe3b-3ac6-84c2-e5050f9c790c", "product": {"name": "Linux"}, "product_version": "1da177e4c3f41524e886b7f1b8a0c1fc7321cac2 <54fa25ffab2b700df5abd58c136d64a912c53953"}, {"id": "cec314f1-93ec-3fc2-bb31-f86d0b4ecc2c", "product": {"name": "Linux"}, "product_version": "patch: 5.10.177"}, {"id": "cf5ff6aa-fda5-361c-93cc-dadb73a95a42", "product": {"name": "Linux"}, "product_version":